post_text:
Dear CFSD Families,

Great news!

Yesterday the USDA announced that they are extending free meals for kids through December 31, 2020.

This means that our free grab-and-go breakfast and lunch food service will resume Wednesday, September 2, 7:30 am - 10:30 am, for any children who are 1-18 years of age. Please refer to the flyer below for additional information.

As with our summer program, families will receive the food bags curbside. Parents may pick up meals for their children. No student ID, student number, or student name is required.

We will offer the same three locations for pickup:

Orange Grove Middle School
1911 E Orange Grove Road

Catalina Foothills High School
4300 E Sunrise Drive

Canyon View Elementary School
5725 N Sabino Canyon Road

With this program, our students will have the healthy food they need so they are ready to learn, play and grow.

Sincerely,

Mary Kamerzell
Superintendent

post_text: At Tuesday night's governing board meeting, these community-minded CFHS students were recognized for their summer project: making 380 face shields for CFSD staff.
shared_text:
Catalina Foothills High School
August 27 at 3:28 PM ·

The CFSD Governing Board recognized one of our robotics teams for their act of service on behalf of our teachers.

The high school's Pioneer 327 Robotics team made and donated 380 face shields for CFSD staff. Their statement about why: "We consider service to our community to be the most core aspect of being an FTC (FIRST Tech Challenge) team. This shield donation is a natural extension of that philosophy, and we're very thankful to CFHS and all of our other 3D printer donors which made it possible."

The team raised donations to cover the cost of the filament, elastic and transparencies. The team followed Cornell University's design for the Prusa shield, which is a high-quality, durable, adjustable style. The shield can be wiped down with a disinfecting wipe, and it can be comfortably worn over a face mask. If the transparency is damaged, the team can replace it.

Thank you for helping us protect our precious staff, Pioneer!

July 25, 2020

Dear CFSD Community,

It has come to my attention that families may believe that we will ignore an Arizona Department of Health Services' (ADHS) anticipated August 7 metric that may indicate that it is not safe to reopen our schools in-person on August 17. That is not true. It is unimaginable that Governor Ducey will not heed the ADHS metric if it indicates that Arizona schools are not safe to reopen. Regardless, we will take the ADHS metric seriously and follow its advice.

Sincerely,
Mary Kamerzell

post_text:
A Message from CFSD Superintendent Kamerzell re:
Reopening for 2020-2021

June 16, 2020

Dear CFSD Community,

I want to provide a brief update about the planning effort that is underway to reopen CFSD for the 2020-2021 school year. We are working on two options for families:

Full-time in-person learning (brick-and-mortar school)
Full-time remote learning

We did explore offering a blended/hybrid option for combined part-time in-person learning with part-time remote learning. We abandoned that option because it is an unreasonable work expectation of our teachers to provide both without adding a significant benefit to students.

Much more planning and preparation remain before details are finalized. We want to share the plans with you no later than early July so that you have time to make a decision about which option best serves the needs of your family.

In the meantime, please know that this planning is driven by our commitment to protect the health and safety of students and staff, and sustain a robust learning environment.

Sincerely,

Mary Kamerzell

Esperero Canyon Middle School
May 9 at 11:31 AM ·

🎼FROM MS. HIGGINS🎼
Presenting our finished "Virtual Choir" video! I had so much fun putting this together and I hope it brings a smile to your face to listen/watch our students sing during this crazy time.

This song, "When I Grow Up," was supposed to be our closing song for the combined Canyon View, Ventana Vista, and Esperero choir concert that was cancelled due to the school closures. A couple of weeks ago, we asked students to record videos of themselves singing their part for this optional project.

This final product has students from all 3 of our schools in grades 2 through 7. There are 36 students mixed into the audio and 34 in the video (a couple of students only recorded audio).

Featured soloists are Lila Poore (6th grade) and Siena Mayfield (7th grade).

A huge thanks to Mrs. Moore and Mr. Colwell for teaching their students the song and helping me collect the videos on their Google Classroom sites!

I hope you enjoy these sweet voices! :) I look forward to hearing them again in person soon!
--Ms. Julia Higgins

A couple of weeks ago, we asked students to record videos of themselves singing their part for this optional project.

This final product has students from all 3 of our schools in grades 2 through 7. There are 36 students mixed into the audio and 34 in the video (a couple of students only recorded audio).

Featured soloists are Lila Poore (6th grade) and Siena Mayfield (7th grade).

A huge thanks to Mrs. Moore and Mr. Colwell for teaching their students the song and helping me collect the videos on their Google Classroom sites!

I hope you enjoy these sweet voices! :) I look forward to hearing them again in person soon!
--Ms. Julia Higgins

post_text:
TWO THOUSAND MEALS SERVED THIS WEEK
Wow! We are having so much fun serving meals to our students and other students within the community. Our meal counts have been increasing each day and today we expect our total meal count will be over 2,000 for the first week of service.

We've had families return to the same site every day which is really
encouraging. Parents often express gratitude while their kids are
excited to see what is in their bags. We had a family give a thank
you card to our staff at Canyon View and a boy gave us Chinese
Knots at the high school. We've had parents and kids ride up on
bicycles to get their meals. Some families bring everybody along for
the outing - dogs included.

Next week’s menus are posted below. We have 3 locations: Canyon View Elementary School, Catalina Foothills High School and Orange Grove Middle School, with service from 8 a.m. - 10:30 a.m. Thank you for your support of our grab-and-go meal program, with free breakfast and lunch for everyone ages 1-18.

Valley View Early Learning Center
April 3 at 1:47 PM ·

From Ms. Kristy

This week VVELC teachers began our online learning program with good morning meeting, activities for the day, read aloud, and music and movement. Here are Lilah and Ella doing yoga mermaid pose, and Derick is doing zebra pose.

This is my lesson on feelings: How are you feeling today? Are you lonely because you miss your friends? Are you happy because you get to be with your family? Are you mad because you want to go to the playground but you can't?

Each day I remind my students I miss you, I love you, and you are safe.

At VVELC, we teach curriculum of the heart. ❤️

post_text:
Some parents are asking about how Governor Ducey's Stay Home, Stay Healthy, Stay Connected order affects our Chromebook distribution this week.

It won't. The distribution schedule for Chromebooks in Catalina Foothills School District remains scheduled for Wednesday and Thursday of this week. Under Governor Ducey’s order, 'distribution of equipment needed to work from home and assignments for completion of distance learning' are defined as Essential Activities.

Remember, if you have multiple students and have reserved more than one Chromebook, please pick up the devices at the school of your student’s highest grade level on Wednesday between 8am – 11am or Thursday from 3-5:30. Thank you!

Dear Parents/Guardians,

The district compiled a list of resources that can be used for at-home learning activities during the school closure. They can be found at the link below.

The list of resources is not comprehensive. It is meant to be used as a menu from which to explore and select activities of interest for your student(s). Keep it fun and explore new ideas or use the resources as a vehicle to practice skills and keep learning fresh.

The learning resources and activities are not required. Please do not submit any activities that your child completes. Teachers will not be contacting parents/students during this time.

CFSD is developing a plan for remote learning for all students should it be needed. Future communications will provide information about when/if a remote learning environment is required. We appreciate your patience and understanding during this unprecedented time.

post_text:
CFHS Theatre Arts Presents Disaster! The Musical.
Summary: New York's hottest A-listers are lining up for the opening of The Barracuda, the brand new floating casino and discotheque. Also on board is a faded disco star, a sexy nightclub singer with her eleven-year-old twins, a disaster expert, a feminist reporter, an older couple with a secret, a pair of young guys who are looking for ladies, an untrustworthy businessman and a nun with a gambling addiction. What begins as a night of boogie fever quickly changes to panic as the ship succumbs to multiple disasters, such as earthquakes, tidal waves, fire, sharks, and rats! Who will survive? Come aboard this ship to find out and be prepared to sing along!

Dates: March 6, 7, 12, 13, 14 at 7:30pm and a matinee on March 8 at 2:00pm

Tickets are $12 on Intouch or at the door. They can also be purchased by contacting the CFHS Bursar at (520) 209-8317

post_text: How can DECA help prepare your student for college & career?
shared_text:
Catalina Foothills High School
February 25 at 1:31 PM ·

DECA STUDENTS FIND SUCCESS AT STATE

At the DECA State Career Development Conference, an 18-strong student team coached by Mr. Jason Reinhardt represented CFHS in multiple business and entrepreneurship events. The competition took place in Phoenix on February 21-23.

Lauren Vaz and Alexis Tretschok placed fourth in the Entrepreneurship event.

Melanie Dasch placed fifth in the Principles of Hospitality and Tourism event.

Melanie Dasch and Maddie Ballis won exam medals for scoring in the top 10% in the state.

Mariah Rocha, Isabella Estrella, Eddie Uche, and Joseph Vouvakis took home medals as section winners of their events.

Lauren, Alexis and Melanie now advance to the International Career Development Conference (ICDC) in Nashville, TN, April 28-May 3. Congratulations to Mr. Reinhardt and these student leaders!

post_text: Congratulations to our newest robotics team!
shared_text:
Catalina Foothills High School
February 23 at 7:50 PM ·

Robotics Team Wins at State
At the FIRST Tech Challenge state championship in Flagstaff, our high school robotics team Pioneer 327 won the Motivate Award for exhibiting outstanding teamwork and sparking enthusiasm for robotics. Forty-eight teams representing Arizona, California, New Mexico, Colorado and Mexico competed for one of five major awards (Inspire, Motivate, Connect, Think and Design) so it’s an extraordinary feat that our high school students are bringing one of these special trophies home to CFHS.

Congratulations to
Josh Barlow
Ben Seckeler
Braden Cantor-Goldner
David Berk
Delaney Endean
Dexi Lin
Gianluca Tenino
Jeremy Wang
Joseph Cohen
Nik Gruber
Noah Wellman
Josh Tint
Danny Clayton
Jerry Barela
And to Coaches Charlotte Ackerman and Mark Haye.

SUPER VOLUNTEER RECOGNITION
At Tuesday night's meeting, the governing board recognized Travis Dover as a super volunteer. Board Member Amy Bhola reviewed the volunteer efforts of Travis, who is a freshman at Catalina Foothills High School and an alumnus of Sunrise Drive.

Travis’s idea was to support students’ sense of belonging and to offer sensory experiences for all students at Sunrise Drive by creating a colorful sensory path on the playground. Travis’s project exemplifies the part of the CFSD mission of “a caring, collaborative community.”

Esperero 7th Graders Bryan Zhang is CFSD's 2020 spelling bee champion. Esperero 8th Grader Greta Moore is the 2nd place winner. Both Bryan and Greta will move on to compete in the Pima County Spelling Bee in February.

Congratulations to all CFSD school winners who moved onto the district competition: Canyon View - Taryn Smith and Milo Smith; Manzanita - Alex Yetka, Colin Gooden, Shay Wong; Sunrise Drive - Xeeyara Quiambao, Elsie Bazarnic, Liliana Ruiz; Ventana Vista - Orian Vogiatzis, Sophie Al Nassif; Esperero - Bryan Zahng, Siena Mayfield, and Greta Moore.
